  "mdx-no-more": {
    info: {
      id: 14,
      slug: "mdx-no-more",
      title: "Bye Bye MDX, Hello MD!",
      description:
        "Rename all .mdx files to .md because your plugin can't handle the fancy stuff.",
      difficulty: "hard",
      tags: ["mv", "find", "xargs", "sed", "grep"],
      testcases: [
        {
          id: 1,
          public: true,
          expected_fs: {
            "intro_to_terminal.md":
              "# Terminal: Your Digital Superpower\n\nThe terminal is not just a tool; it's a way of life.\\\nHere, commands are your spells, and scripts are your potions.\\\nMaster it, and you'll unlock the secrets of your machine.\n\n---\n\n## Quick Starter Commands\n\n- `ls`: Peek into your current directory.\n- `mkdir`: Create new directories\u2014because organization matters.\n- `cat`: Read files like a curious detective.\n\nPro Tip: Combine commands with pipes (`|`) for ultimate efficiency!\n",
            "linux_basics.md":
              "# Linux Basics: Start Here\n\nLinux isn't just an OS; it's an adventure.\\\nFrom file permissions to process management, there's always something new to learn.\n\n---\n\n## Essential Commands\n\n1. `chmod`: Change file permissions like a boss.\n1. `ps`: See what's running under the hood.\n1. `grep`: Find text in files faster than Ctrl+F.\n\nFun Fact: Linux powers most of the internet, so you're learning something truly global.\n",
            "page.md":
              "# EasyShell: Your Terminal Buddy\n\nWelcome to the world of shell scripting!\nHere, every keystroke is a step closer to automation glory.\nRemember: The shell isn't scary\u2014it's just misunderstood.\n",
          },
        },
        {
          id: 2,
          public: true,
          expected_fs: {
            "regex.txt":
              '# Regex Cheatsheet for Linux Command Lovers\n\nRegular expressions (regex) are your secret weapon for text matching.\n\n---\n\n## Common Patterns\n\n1. `^`: Matches the start of a line.  \n   Example: `^Hello` matches "Hello" at the beginning of a line.  \n\n2. `$`: Matches the end of a line.  \n   Example: `World$` matches "World" at the end of a line.  \n\n3. `.`: Matches any single character.  \n   Example: `h.t` matches "hat", "hit", or "hot".  \n\n4. `*`: Matches zero or more occurrences of the preceding character.  \n   Example: `he*llo` matches "hello", "hllo", or "heeeello".\n\nPro Tip: Combine regex with commands like `grep`, `awk`, or `sed` for ultimate text manipulation.\n\n',
            "src/file-management.md":
              '# File Operations in Linux\n\nFiles are the heart of any operating system, and Linux gives you superpowers to manage them.\n\n---\n\n## Key Commands for File Operations\n\n- `touch`: Create an empty file faster than you can say "new file."\n- `mv`: Move or rename files like a ninja.\n- `cp`: Copy files\u2014because backups are your best friend.\n- `rm`: Delete files... but remember, with great power comes great responsibility.\n\nPro Tip: Always use `ls` before running `rm` to avoid accidental disasters!\n',
            "src/index.html": "",
            "src/process_management.md":
              "# Process Management 101\n\nYour computer is always busy, but with Linux, you\u2019re the boss of all processes.\n\n---\n\n## Essential Process Commands\n\n- `top`: Spy on your system's activity in real-time.\n- `kill`: Politely (or not-so-politely) ask a process to stop.\n- `jobs`: Keep track of background tasks like a multitasking pro.\n- `bg` and `fg`: Move jobs between the background and foreground effortlessly.\n\nFun Fact: The PID (Process ID) is like your process\u2019s social security number.\n",
            "pages/debugging_tips.md":
              "# Debugging Tips for Shell Scripts\n\nDebugging isn't scary; it's just problem-solving with extra steps.\\\nHere\u2019s how to fix those annoying errors in your scripts.\n\n---\n\n## Steps to Debug\n\n1. Add `set -e` to stop the script when errors occur.\n1. Use `echo` generously\u2014print variables, commands, and results.\n1. Check file paths and permissions\u2014they\u2019re often the culprits.\n\nMantra: _\"Every error is an opportunity to learn.\"_\n",
            "pages/shell-humor.md":
              "# Shell Humor to Keep You Sane\n\nCoding can be stressful, but laughter is the best debugging tool!\n\n---\n\n## Terminal Jokes\n\n- Why did the script refuse to run? It wasn\u2019t feeling executable today!\n- What\u2019s a programmer\u2019s favorite coffee? JavaScript!\n- Why do shell commands never get lost? They always know their path (`$PATH`).\n\nRemember, every error message has a punchline waiting to be discovered.\n",
            "app/bash_tricks.md":
              "# Bash Tricks for Cool Coders\n\nBash isn't just a shell; it's a playground for creative coding.\\\nLearn these tricks to impress your friends (and yourself).\n\n---\n\n## Bash Magic\n\n- Use `alias` to create shortcuts for your favorite commands.\n- Use `$()` for command substitution\u2014it\u2019s like magic in parentheses.\n- Use loops (`for`, `while`) to automate repetitive tasks.\n\nPro Tip: Combine loops with conditionals (`if`, `else`) for ultimate scripting power.\n",
          },
        },
        {
          id: 3,
          public: false,
          expected_fs: {
            "commands.json":
              '{\n  "shell_tips": [\n    {\n      "command": "ls",\n      "description": "List files and directories."\n    },\n    {\n      "command": "cd",\n      "description": "Change directory."\n    },\n    {\n      "command": "grep",\n      "description": "Search for patterns in text."\n    },\n    {\n      "command": "chmod",\n      "description": "Change file permissions."\n    },\n    {\n      "command": "echo",\n      "description": "Print text to the terminal."\n    }\n  ],\n  "pro_tip": "Combine commands using pipes (|) for powerful workflows!"\n}\n',
            "scripting.md":
              "# Shell Scripting Tips & Tricks\n\nWriting shell scripts is part art, part science, and all fun!\n\n---\n\n## Tips for Better Scripts\n\n1. Always start with a shebang (`#!/bin/bash`). It\u2019s like saying \u201CHey, I\u2019m a script!\u201D\n1. Use comments (`#`) generously\u2014future-you will thank you later.\n1. Test scripts on sample data before running them on important files.\n\nPro Tip: Modularize your script by using functions\u2014it makes debugging easier.\n",
            "pages/terminal-shortcuts.md":
              "# Terminal Shortcuts You Need to Know\n\nSave time and type less with these handy shortcuts.\n\n---\n\n## Must-Know Shortcuts\n\n- **Ctrl + C**: Stop whatever\u2019s running (your panic button).\n- **Ctrl + Z**: Pause a process and send it to the background.\n- **Ctrl + R**: Search through command history like a time traveler.\n- **Tab**: Auto-complete commands or file names\u2014because typing is hard.\n\nPro Tip: Mastering shortcuts makes you look cooler than any GUI user.\n",
            "blogs/permissions.md":
              "# Mastering File Permissions in Linux\n\nPermissions are how Linux keeps your files safe from nosy neighbors (and yourself).\n\n---\n\n## Permission Basics\n\n- **r**: Read (look but don\u2019t touch).\n- **w**: Write (make changes).\n- **x**: Execute (run it like a program).\n\nUse `chmod` to change permissions, and `ls -l` to see them in action.\n\nPro Tip: Use octal notation (`chmod 755`) for faster permission changes\u2014it\u2019s geeky but efficient!\n",
            "app/networking.commands.md":
              "# Networking Commands for Linux Wizards\n\nNetworking on Linux is like being a digital detective. These commands help you investigate and connect.\n\n---\n\n## Networking Essentials\n\n1. `ping`: Check if a server is alive (or just ignoring you).\n1. `curl`: Fetch data from URLs\u2014because browsers are overrated.\n1. `ifconfig` or `ip addr`: Inspect your network interfaces like a pro.\n1. `netstat`: See who\u2019s talking to your machine over the network.\n\nPro Tip: Use `traceroute` to follow the path your packets take\u2014it\u2019s like GPS for data.\n",
          },
        },
      ],
    },
  },
